# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: retro-z80-assembly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **8-bit** integers or other data units are those that are 8 bits wide (1 octet).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Also, 8-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers or data buses of that size.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Memory addresses (and thus address buses) for 8-bit CPUs are generally larger than 8-bit, usually 16-bit.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The term '8-bit' is also applied to the character sets that could be used on computers with 8-bit bytes, the best known being various forms of extended ASCII, including the ISO/IEC 8859 series of national character sets – especially Latin 1 for English and Western European languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The IBM System/360 introduced byte-addressable memory with 8-bit bytes, as opposed to bit-addressable or decimal digit-addressable or word-addressable memory, although its general-purpose registers were 32 bits wide, and addresses were contained in the lower 24 bits of those addresses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Different models of System/360 had different internal data path widths; the IBM System/360 Model 30 (1965) implemented the 32-bit System/360 architecture, but had an 8-bit native path width, and performed 32-bit arithmetic 8 bits at a time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The first widely adopted 8-bit microprocessor was the Intel 8080, being used in many hobbyist computers of the late 1970s and early 1980s, often running the CP/M operating system; it had 8-bit data words and 16-bit addresses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Zilog Z80 (compatible with the 8080) and the Motorola 6800 were also used in similar computers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Z80 and the MOS Technology 6502 8-bit CPUs were widely used in home computers and second- and third-generation game consoles of the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Many 8-bit CPUs or microcontrollers are the basis of today's ubiquitous embedded systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microprocessors were the first widely used microprocessors in the computing industry, marking a major shift from mainframes and minicomputers to smaller, more affordable systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The introduction of 8-bit processors in the 1970s enabled the production of personal computers, leading to the popularization of computing and setting the foundation for the modern computing landscape.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The 1976 Zilog Z80, one of the most popular 8-bit CPUs (though with 4-bit ALU, at least in the original), was discontinued in 2024 (its product line Z84C00), with Last Time Buy (LTB) orders by 14 June 2024.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] An 8-bit register can store 28 different values.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 8 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 255 (28 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −128 (−1 × 27) through 127 (27 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit CPUs use an 8-bit data bus and can therefore access 8 bits of data in a single machine instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The address bus is typically a double octet (16 bits) wide, due to practical and economical considerations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] This implies a direct address space of 64 KB (65,536 bytes) on most 8-bit processors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Most home computers from the 8-bit era fully exploited the address space, such as the BBC Micro (Model B) with 32 KB of RAM plus 32 KB of ROM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Commodore 128, and other 8-bit systems, meaning still with 16-bit addressing, could use more than 64 KB, i.e.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] 128 KB RAM, also the BBC Master with it expandable to 512 KB of RAM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Some index registers, such as the two in the 6502, are 8-bit.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] This limits the size of the arrays addressed using indexed addressing instructions to objects of up to 256 bytes (28 bytes) without requiring more complicated code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Other 8-bit CPUs, such as the Motorola 6800 and Intel 8080, have 16-bit index registers.*"Interview with William Mensch, 1995 October 09".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] *Silicon Genesis: Oral Histories of Semiconductor Technology*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The first commercial 8-bit processor was the Intel 8008 (1972) which was originally intended for the Datapoint 2200 intelligent terminal.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Most competitors to Intel started off with such character oriented 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Modernized variants of these 8-bit machines are still one of the most common types of processor in embedded systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] The MOS Technology 6502, and variants of it, were used in personal computers, such as the Apple I, Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, BBC Micro, PET, VIC-20, and in home video game consoles such as the Atari 2600 and the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit processors continue to be designed for general education about computer hardware, as well as for hobbyists' interests.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] One such CPU was designed and implemented using 7400-series integrated circuits on a breadboard.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/8-bit-computing] Designing 8-bit CPUs and their respective assemblers is a common training exercise for engineering students, engineers, and hobbyists.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The **Intel 8080** is an 8-bit microprocessor produced by Intel, first released in April 1974.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It served as the successor to the 8008, despite not being binary compatible with it.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Originally intended for use in embedded systems such as calculators, cash registers, computer terminals, and industrial robots, the 8080 became a popular processor used across a wide range of devices, and contributed to the rise of the microcomputer industry.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Several key design choices contributed to the 8080’s success.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Its 40‑pin package simplified interfacing compared to the 8008’s 18‑pin design, enabling a more efficient data bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The transition to NMOS technology provided faster transistor speeds than the 8008's PMOS, also making it TTL compatible.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] An expanded instruction set and a full 16-bit address bus allowed the 8080 to access up to 64 KB of memory, quadrupling the capacity of its predecessor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A broader selection of support chips further enhanced its functionality.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Many of these improvements stemmed from customer feedback, as designer Federico Faggin and others at Intel heard from industry about shortcomings in the 8008 architecture.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 found its way into early personal computers such as the Altair 8800 and subsequent S-100 bus systems, and it served as the original target CPU for the CP/M operating system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It directly influenced the later x86 architecture, which was designed so that its assembly language closely resembled that of the 8080, permitting many instructions to map directly from one to the other.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Originally operating at a clock rate of 2 MHz, with common instructions taking between 4 and 11 clock cycles, the 8080 was capable of executing several hundred thousand instructions per second.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Later, two faster variants, the 8080A-1 and 8080A-2, offered improved clock speeds of 3.125 MHz and 2.63 MHz, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] In most applications, the processor was paired with two support chips, the 8224 clock generator/driver and the 8228 bus controller, to manage its timing and data flow.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Microprocessor customers were reluctant to adopt the 8008 because of limitations such as the single addressing mode, low clock speed, low pin count, and small on-chip stack, which restricted the scale and complexity of software.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] There were several proposed designs for the 8080, ranging from simply adding stack instructions to the 8008 to a complete departure from all previous Intel architectures.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The final design was a compromise between the proposals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The conception of the 8080 began in the summer of 1971, when Intel wrapped up development of the 4004 and were still working on the 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] After rumors about the "CPU on a chip" came out, Intel started to see interest in the microprocessor from all sorts of customers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] At the same time, Federico Faggin – who led the design of the 4004 and became the primary architect of the 8080 – was giving some technical seminars on both of the aforementioned microprocessors and visiting customers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Faggin later proposed the chip to Intel's management and pushed for its implementation in the spring of 1972, as development of the 8008 was wrapping up.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Much to his surprise and frustration, however, Intel didn't approve the project.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Faggin says that Intel wanted to see how the market would react to the 4004 and 8008 first, while others noted the problems Intel was having getting its latest generation of memory chips out the door and wanted to focus on that.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] As a result, Intel didn't approve of the project until fall of that year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Faggin hired Masatoshi Shima, who helped design the logic of the 4004 with him, from Japan in November 1972.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Shima did the detailed design under Faggin's direction, using the design methodology for random logic with silicon gate that Faggin had created for the 4000 family and the 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 was explicitly designed to be a general-purpose microprocessor for a larger number of customers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Much of the development effort was spent trying to integrate the functionalities of the 8008's supplemental chips into one package.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It was decided early in development that the 8080 was not to be binary-compatible with the 8008, instead opting for source compatibility once run through a transpiler, to allow new software to not be subject to the same restrictions as the 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] For the same reason, as well as to expand the capabilities of stack-based routines and interrupts, the stack was moved to external memory.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Noting the specialized use of general-purpose registers by programmers in mainframe systems, Faggin with Shima and Stanley Mazor decided the 8080's registers would be specialized, with register pairs having a different set of uses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This also allowed the engineers to more effectively use transistors for other purposes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Shima finished the layout in August 1973.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Production of the chip later began in December of that year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] After the development of NMOS logic fabrication, a prototype of the 8080 was completed in January 1974.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It had a flaw, in that driving with standard TTL devices increased the ground voltage because high current flowed into the narrow line.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Intel had already produced 40,000 units of the 8080 at the direction of the sales section before Shima characterized the prototype.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] After working out some typical last-minute issues, Intel introduced the product in March 1974.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It was released a month later as requiring Low-power Schottky TTL (LS TTL) devices.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Intel offered an instruction set simulator for the 8080 named INTERP/80 to run compiled PL/M programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It was written in FORTRAN IV by Gary Kildall while he worked as a consultant for Intel.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] There is only one patent on the 8080 with the following names: Federico Faggin, Masatoshi Shima, Stanley Mazor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The Intel 8080 is the successor to the 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It uses the same basic instruction set and register model as the 8008, although it is neither source code compatible nor binary code compatible with its predecessor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Every instruction in the 8008 has an equivalent instruction in the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 also adds 16-bit operations in its instruction set.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Whereas the 8008 required the use of the HL register pair to indirectly access its 14-bit memory space, the 8080 has addressing modes to directly access its full 16-bit memory space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The internal 7-level push-down call stack of the 8008 was replaced by a dedicated 16-bit stack-pointer (SP) register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080's 40-pin DIP packaging provides a 16-bit address bus and an 8-bit data bus that more efficiently access 64 KiB (216 bytes) of memory.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The processor has seven 8-bit registers (A, B, C, D, E, H, and L), where A is the primary 8-bit accumulator.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The other six registers can be used as either individual 8-bit registers or in three 16-bit register pairs (BC, DE, and HL, referred to as B, D and H in Intel documents) depending on the particular instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Some instructions can also use the HL register pair as a (limited) 16-bit accumulator.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A pseudo-register M, which refers to the dereferenced memory location pointed to by HL, can be used almost anywhere other registers can be used.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 has a 16-bit stack pointer to memory, replacing the 8008's internal stack, and a 16-bit program counter.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The processor maintains internal flag bits (a status register), which indicate the results of arithmetic and logical instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Only certain instructions affect the flags.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The carry bit can be set or complemented by specific instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Conditional-branch instructions test the various flag status bits.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The accumulator and the flags together are called the PSW, or program status word.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] PSW can be pushed to or popped from the stack.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] As with many other 8-bit processors, all instructions are encoded in one byte (including register numbers, but excluding immediate data), for simplicity.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Some can be followed by one or two bytes of data, which can be an immediate operand, a memory address, or a port number.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Like more advanced processors, it has automatic CALL and RET instructions for multi-level procedure calls and returns (which can even be conditionally executed, like jumps) and instructions to save and restore any 16-bit register pair on the machine stack.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Eight one-byte call instructions (`RST`) for subroutines exist at the fixed addresses 00h, 08h, 10h, ..., 38h.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] These are intended to be supplied by external hardware in order to invoke a corresponding interrupt service routine, but are also often employed as fast system calls.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The slowest instruction is `XTHL`, which exchanges the register pair HL with the last item pushed on the stack.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] All 8-bit ALU operations with two operands can only be performed on the 8-bit accumulator (the A register).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The other operand can be either an immediate value, another 8-bit register, or a memory byte addressed by the 16-bit register pair HL.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Increments and decrements can be performed on any 8 bit register or an HL-addressed memory byte.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Direct copying is supported between any two 8-bit registers and between any 8-bit register and an HL-addressed memory byte.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Due to the regular encoding of the `MOV` instruction (using a quarter of available opcode space), there are redundant codes to copy a register into itself (`MOV B,B`, for instance), which are of little use, except for delays.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The systematic opcode for `MOV M,M` is instead used to encode the halt (`HLT`) instruction, halting execution until an external reset or interrupt occurs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Although the 8080 is generally an 8-bit processor, it has limited abilities to perform 16-bit operations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Any of the three 16-bit register pairs (BC, DE, or HL, referred to as B, D, H in Intel documents) or SP can be loaded with an immediate 16-bit value (using `LXI`), incremented or decremented (using `INX` and `DCX`), or added to HL (using `DAD`).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] By adding HL to itself, it is possible to achieve the same result as a 16-bit arithmetical left shift with one instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The only 16-bit instructions that affect any flag is `DAD`, which sets the CY (carry) flag in order to allow for programmed 24-bit or 32-bit arithmetic (or larger), needed to implement floating-point arithmetic.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] BC, DE, HL, or PSW can be copied to and from the stack using `PUSH` and `POP`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A stack frame can be allocated using `DAD SP` and `SPHL`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A branch to a computed pointer can be executed with `PCHL`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] `LHLD` loads HL from directly addressed memory and `SHLD` stores HL likewise.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The `XCHG` instruction exchanges the values of the HL and DE register pairs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] `XTHL`exchanges last item pushed on stack with HL.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] None of these 16-bit operations were supported on the earlier Intel 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 supports 256 input/output (I/O) ports, accessed via dedicated I/O instructions taking port addresses as operands.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Generating the control signals for selecting between RAM and I/O is usually aided by a support chip (8212 or 8228).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This I/O mapping scheme is regarded as an advantage, as it frees up the processor's limited address space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Many CPU architectures instead use so-called memory-mapped I/O (MMIO), in which a common address space is used for both RAM and peripheral chips.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This removes the need for dedicated I/O instructions, although a drawback in such designs may be that special hardware must be used to insert wait states, as peripherals are often slower than memory.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] In some simple 8080 computers, however, I/O is indeed addressed as if they were memory cells, "memory-mapped", leaving the I/O commands unused.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] I/O addressing can also sometimes employ the fact that the processor outputs the same 8-bit port address to both the lower and the higher address byte (i.e., `IN 05h` would put the address 0505h on the 16-bit address bus).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Similar I/O-port schemes are used in the backward-compatible Zilog Z80 and Intel 8085, and the closely related x86 microprocessor families.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] One of the bits in the processor state word (see below) indicates that the processor is accessing data from the stack.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Using this signal, it is possible to implement a separate stack memory space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] For more advanced systems, during the beginning of each machine cycle, the processor places an eight bit status word on the data bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This byte contains flags that determine whether the memory or I/O port is accessed and whether it is necessary to handle an interrupt.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The interrupt system state (enabled or disabled) is also output on a separate pin.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] For simple systems, where the interrupts are not used, it is possible to find cases where this pin is used as an additional single-bit output port (the popular Radio-86RK computer made in the Soviet Union, for instance).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Hardware interrupts are initiated by asserting the interrupt request (INT) pin.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] At the next opcode fetch cycle (M1), the interrupt will be acknowledged with the INTA state code.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] At this time, an instruction is "jammed" (Intel's word) by external hardware on the data bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This can be a one-byte `RST` instruction, or if using an Intel 8259, a `CALL` instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Interrupts may be enabled and disabled with `EI` and `DI` instructions, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Interrupts are disabled after an INTA; they must be re-enabled explicitly by the interrupt service routine.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 does not support non-maskable interrupts.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The following 8080/8085 assembler source code is for a subroutine named `memcpy` that copies a block of data bytes of a given size from one location to another.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The data block is copied one byte at a time, and the data movement and looping logic utilizes 16-bit operations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The address bus has its own 16 pins, and the data bus has 8 pins that are usable without any multiplexing.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Using the two additional pins (read and write signals), it is possible to assemble simple microprocessor devices very easily.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Only the separate IO space, interrupts, and DMA need added chips to decode the processor pin signals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Nonetheless, the pin load capacity is limited; even simple computers often require bus amplifiers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The processor needs three power sources (−5, +5, and +12 V) and two non-overlapping high-amplitude synchronizing signals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Nonetheless, at least the late Soviet version КР580ВМ80А was able to work with a single +5 V power source, the +12 V pin being connected to +5 V and the −5 V pin to ground.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 integrated circuit has an NMOS design, which employed non‑saturated enhancement mode transistors as loads, which demanded supplementary voltage levels (+12 V and −5 V) alongside the standard TTL compatible +5 V.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It was manufactured in a silicon gate process using a minimal feature size of 6 μm.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A single layer of metal is used to interconnect the approximately 4,500 transistors in the design, but the higher resistance polysilicon layer, which required higher voltage for some interconnects, is implemented with transistor gates.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 was used in many early microcomputers, such as the MITS Altair 8800 Computer, Processor Technology SOL-20 Terminal Computer and IMSAI 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] It formed the basis for the CP/M operating system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] In 1979, after the introduction of the Z80 and 8085 processors, five manufacturers of the 8080 were selling an estimated 500,000 units per month at a price around $3 to $4 each.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The first single-board microcomputers, such as MYCRO-1 and the *dyna-micro* / MMD-1 (see: Single-board computer) were based on the Intel 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] One of the early uses of the 8080 was made in the late 1970s by Cubic-Western Data of San Diego, California, in its Automated Fare Collection Systems custom designed for mass transit systems around the world.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] An early industrial use of the 8080 is as the "brain" of the DatagraphiX Auto-COM (Computer Output Microfiche) line of products, which takes large amounts of user data from reel-to-reel tape and images it onto microfiche.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The Auto-COM instruments also include an entire automated film cutting, processing, washing, and drying sub-system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Several early arcade video games were built around the 8080 microprocessor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The first commercially available arcade video game to incorporate a microprocessor was *Gun Fight*, Midway Games' 8080-based reimplementation of Taito's discrete-logic *Western Gun*, which was released in November 1975.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] (A pinball machine that incorporated a Motorola 6800 processor, *The Spirit of '76*, had already been released the previous month.) The 8080 was then used in later Midway arcade video games and in Taito's 1978 *Space Invaders*, one of the most successful and well-known of all arcade video games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Zilog introduced the Z80, which has a compatible machine language instruction set and initially used the same assembly language as the 8080, but for legal reasons, Zilog developed a syntactically-different (but code compatible) alternative assembly language for the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] At Intel, the 8080 was followed by the compatible and electrically more elegant 8085.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Later, Intel issued the assembly-language compatible (but not binary-compatible) 16-bit 8086 and then the 8/16-bit 8088, which was selected by IBM for its new PC to be launched in 1981.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Later NEC made the NEC V20 (an 8088 clone with Intel 80186 instruction set compatibility) which also supports an 8080 emulation mode.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This is also supported by NEC's V30 (a similarly enhanced 8086 clone).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Thus, the 8080, via its instruction set architecture (ISA), made a lasting impact on computer history.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] As of 2017, the 8080 is still in production at Lansdale Semiconductors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 also changed how computers were created.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] When the 8080 was introduced, computer systems were usually created by computer manufacturers such as Digital Equipment Corporation, Hewlett-Packard, or IBM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] A manufacturer would produce the whole computer, including processor, terminals, and system software such as compilers and operating system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 was designed for almost any application *except* a complete computer system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Hewlett-Packard developed the HP 2640 series of smart terminals around the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The HP 2647 is a terminal that runs the programming language BASIC on the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Microsoft's founding product, Microsoft BASIC, was originally programmed for the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The 8080 and 8085 gave rise to the 8086, which was designed as a source code compatible, albeit not binary compatible, extension of the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] This design, in turn, later spawned the x86 family of chips, which continue to be Intel's primary line of processors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Many of the 8080's core machine instructions and concepts survive in the widespread x86 platform.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] Examples include the registers named *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D* and many of the flags used to control conditional jumps.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] 8080 assembly code can still be directly translated into x86 instructions, since all of its core elements are still present.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] US patent 4010449, Federico Faggin, Masatoshi Shima, Stanley Mazor, "MOS computer employing a plurality of separate chips", issued March 1, 1977 .
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The first two relate to the status word multiplexed onto the data bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The third claim is for the `RST 7` instruction, which can be invoked by pulling the data bus high.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/intel-8080] The prior art 8008 `RST 7` required more complicated instruction jamming circuitry.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The **Zilog Z80** is an 8-bit microprocessor designed by Zilog, first released in 1976; it played an important role in the evolution of early personal computing.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It was designed to be software-compatible with the Intel 8080, offering a compelling alternative due to its better integration and increased performance.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Along with the 8080's seven registers and flags register, the Z80 introduced an alternate register set, two 16-bit index registers, and additional instructions, including bit manipulation and block copy/search.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 was used in iconic products such as the Osborne 1, Radio Shack TRS-80, ColecoVision, ZX Spectrum, Sega's Master System and the *Pac-Man* arcade cabinet.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In the early 1990s, it was used in portable devices, including the Game Gear and the TI-81 and succeeding graphing calculators.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 was the brainchild of Federico Faggin, a key figure behind the creation of the Intel 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] After leaving Intel in 1974, he co-founded Zilog with Ralph Ungermann.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 debuted in July 1976, and its success allowed Zilog to establish its own chip factories.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] For initial production, Zilog licensed the Z80 to U.S.-based Synertek and Mostek, along with European second-source manufacturer, SGS.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The design was also copied by various Japanese, Eastern European, and Soviet manufacturers gaining global market acceptance as major companies like NEC, Toshiba, Sharp, and Hitachi produced their own versions or compatible clones.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 continued to be used in embedded systems for many years, despite the introduction of more powerful processors; it remained in production until June 2024, 48 years after its original release.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Zilog also continued to enhance the basic design of the Z80 with several successors, including the Z180, Z280, and Z380, with the latest iteration, the eZ80, introduced in 2001 and available for purchase as of 2025.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] At Fairchild Semiconductor, and later at Intel, physicist and engineer Federico Faggin had been working on fundamental transistor and semiconductor manufacturing technology.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] He also developed the basic design methodology used for memories and microprocessors at Intel and led the work on the Intel 4004, the Intel 8080 and several other ICs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Masatoshi Shima was the principal logic and transistor-level designer of the 4004 and the 8080 under Faggin's supervision, while Ralph Ungermann was in charge of custom integrated circuit design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In early 1974, Intel viewed microprocessors not so much as products to be sold on their own but as a way to sell more of its main products, static RAM and ROM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A reorganization placed some of the formerly independent sections under the direction of Les Vadasz, further diluting the microprocessor's place in the company.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] That year, the 1973–1975 recession reached a peak, and Intel laid off several employees.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] All of this led to Faggin becoming restless, and he invited Ungermann out for drinks and asked if he would be interested in starting their own company.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Ungermann immediately agreed, and as he had less to do at Intel, he left in August or September, followed by Faggin, whose last day at Intel was Halloween 1974.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] When Shima heard, he asked to come to the new company as well, but having no actual product design or money, they told him to wait.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The newly formed and unnamed company initially began designing a single-chip microcontroller called the 2001.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] They met with Synertek to discuss fabrication on their lines, and when Faggin began to understand the costs involved, it became clear that a low-cost product like this would not be able to compete with a design from a company with its own production lines, like Intel.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] They then began considering a more complex microprocessor instead, initially known as the Super 80, with the main feature being its use of a +5 V bus instead of the more common −5, +5 and 12 V used by designs like the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The new design was intended to be compatible with the 8080, but add a number of the features of the Motorola 6800, including index registers and improved interrupts.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] While still being set up, the industry newsletter *Electronic News* heard of them and published a story on the newly formed company.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This attracted the attention of Exxon Enterprises, Exxon's high-tech investment arm.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] At the time, in the midst of the recession, there was little venture capital available, with a total of $10 million for the entire industry being spent in all of 1975 (equivalent to $60 million in 2025).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Someone from Exxon contacted the still-unnamed company, and arranged a meeting that eventually led to them providing an initial $500,000 funding in June 1975 (equivalent to $3 million in 2025).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] With funding being discussed and a design to be built, Masatoshi Shima joined in February 1975.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Shima immediately set about producing a high-level design, adding several concepts of his own.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In particular, he used his experience on NEC minicomputers to add the concept of two sets of processor registers so they could quickly respond to interrupts.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Ungerman began the development of a series of related controllers and peripheral chips that would complement the design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Through this period, Shima developed a legendary reputation for being able to convert logic concepts into physical design in realtime; while discussing a proposed feature, he would often interrupt and state how much room that would take on the chip and veto its addition if it was too large.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The first pass at the design was complete by April 1975.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Shima had completed a logic layout by the beginning of May.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A second version of the logic design was issued on August 7 and the bus details by September 16.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Tape-out was completed in November and converting the tape into a production mask required two more months.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Faggin had already started looking for a production partner.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] By this time, Synertek and Mostek had both set up the depletion-mode production lines that could be used to produce the design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Having talked to Synertek previously, Faggin approached them first.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, the president of Synertek demanded that the company be given a second source license, allowing them to sell the design directly.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Faggin thought this would mean they could never compete even if they set up their own lines, and the agreement fell through.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] He then turned to Mostek, who agreed to a term of exclusivity while Zilog got their lines set up, and was eventually given the second source agreement.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] When they met the next day and both immediately recalled it, the company had its name.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The first samples were returned from Mostek on March 9, 1976.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] By the end of the month, they had also completed an assembler-based development system.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Some of the Z80 support and peripheral ICs were under development at this point, and some of them were launched during the following year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Among them were the Z80 CTC (counter/timer), Z80 DMA (direct memory access), Z80 DART (dual asynchronous receiver–transmitter), Z80 SIO (synchronous communication controller), and Z80 PIO (parallel input/output).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 was officially launched in July 1976.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] At the time, concerns existed within the semiconductor industry about the unlicensed reproduction of chip designs by foreign manufacturers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] To help deter reverse engineering, the Zilog team incorporated six "traps", transistors that were subtly modified to behave differently than their appearance would suggest.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] According to Shima, an engineer at NEC later told him that these traps delayed their reverse engineering efforts by six months.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] NEC later settled a patent infringement dispute with Zilog, securing a license to produce authorized versions of the Z80 and other chips.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Following the successful launch of the Z80, Faggin and Ungermann approached Exxon for funding to establish semiconductor fabrication plant.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Exxon agreed, and Zilog built its own production line, enabling the company to capture an estimated 60 to 70 percent of the total market for Z80 sales.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Meanwhile, Mostek was authorized to produce a licensed version of the chip, the MK3880, providing a second source for customers, a safeguard that Intel lacked.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] At the time, second-source agreements were considered essential, particularly for startups like Zilog, which carried a higher risk of business failure and supply disruption.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Faggin designed the instruction set to be binary compatible with the 8080 so that most 8080 code, notably the CP/M operating system and Intel's PL/M compiler for 8080 (as well as its generated code), would run unmodified on the new Z80 CPU.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Masatoshi Shima designed most of the microarchitecture as well as the gate and transistor levels of the Z80 CPU, assisted by a small number of engineers and layout people.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] CEO Federico Faggin was actually heavily involved in the chip layout work, together with two dedicated layout people.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] According to Faggin, he worked 80 hours a week in order to meet the tight schedule given by the financial investors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 took over from the 8080 and its offspring, the 8085, in the processor market and became one of the most popular and widely used 8-bit CPUs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Some organizations such as British Telecom remained loyal to the 8085 for embedded applications, owing to their familiarity with it and to its on-chip serial interface and interrupt architecture.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Likewise, Zenith Data Systems paired the 8085 with the 16-bit Intel 8088 in its first MS-DOS computer, the Zenith Z-100, despite having previous experience with its pioneering Z80-based Heathkit H89 and Zenith Z-89 products.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, other computers were made integrating the Z80 with other CPUs: the Radio Shack TRS-80 Model 16 with a Motorola 68000, the DEC Rainbow with an 8088, and the Commodore 128 with a MOS Technology 8502.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Zilog was later producing a low-power Z80 suitable for the growing laptop computer market of the early 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Intel produced a CMOS 8085 (80C85) used in battery-powered portable computers, such as the Kyocera-designed laptop from April 1983, also sold by Tandy (as TRS-80 Model 100), Olivetti, and NEC.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In following years, however, CMOS versions of the Z80 (from both Zilog and Japanese manufacturers) would dominate this market as well, in products such as the Amstrad NC100, Cambridge Z88 and Tandy's own WP-2.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Perhaps a key to the initial success of the Z80 was the built-in DRAM refresh, at least in markets such as CP/M and other office and home computers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] (Most Z80 embedded systems use static RAM that do not need refresh.) It may also have been its minimalistic two-level interrupt system, or conversely, its general multi-level daisy-chain interrupt system useful in servicing multiple Z80 IO chips.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] These features allowed systems to be built with less support hardware and simpler circuit board layouts.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, others claim that its popularity was due to the duplicated registers that allowed fast context switches or more efficient processing of things like floating-point math compared to 8-bit CPUs with fewer registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] For the original NMOS design, the specified upper clock-frequency limit increased successively from the introductory 2.5 MHz, via the well known 4 MHz (Z80A), up to 6 MHz (Z80B) and 8 MHz (Z80H).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] An NMOS version was produced as a 10 MHz part beginning in the late 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] CMOS versions were developed with specified upper frequency limits ranging from 4 MHz up to 20 MHz for the version sold today.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The CMOS versions allowed low-power standby with internal state retained, having no *lower* frequency limit.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The fully compatible derivatives HD64180/Z180 and eZ80 are currently specified for up to 33 MHz and 50 MHz, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The programming model and register set of the Z80 are fairly conventional, ultimately based on the register structure of the Datapoint 2200.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 was designed as an extension of the Intel 8080, created by the same engineers, which in turn was an extension of the 8008.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The 8008 was basically a PMOS implementation of the TTL-based CPU of the Datapoint 2200.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The 2200 design allowed 8-bit registers H and L (High and Low) to be paired into a 16-bit address register HL.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In the 8080, this pairing was added to the BC and DE pairs as well, while HL was generalized to allow use as a 16-bit accumulator, not just an address register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The 8080 also introduced immediate 16-bit data for BC, DE, HL, and SP loads.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Furthermore, direct 16-bit copying between HL and memory was now possible, using a direct address.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 orthogonalized this further by making all 16-bit register pairs, including IX and IY, more general purpose, as well as allowing 16-bit copying directly to and from memory for all of these pairs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The 16-bit IX and IY registers in the Z80 are primarily intended as base address-registers, where a particular instruction supplies a constant offset that is added to the previous values, but they are also usable as 16-bit accumulators, among other things.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A limitation is that all operand references involving IX or IY require an extra instruction prefix byte, adding at least four clock cycles over the timing of an instruction using HL instead; this sometimes makes using IX or IY less efficient than a method using only the 8080-model registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 also introduced a new signed overflow flag and complemented the fairly simple 16-bit arithmetics of the 8080 with dedicated instructions for *signed* 16-bit arithmetics.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The dual register-set is useful in the embedded role, as it improves interrupt handling performance, but found widespread use in the personal computer role as an additional set of general registers for complex code like floating-point arithmetic or home computer games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The duplicate register file is often referred to as the "alternate register set" (by some, the "primed" register file since the apostrophe character is used to denote them in assembler source code and the Zilog documentation).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This emphasizes that only one set is addressable at any time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, the 8-bit accumulator A with its flag register F is bifurcated from the "general purpose" register pairs HL, DE and BC.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This is accomplished with two separate instructions used to swap their accessibilities: `EX AF,AF'` exchanges only register pair AF with AF', while the `EXX` instruction exchanges the three general purpose register pairs HL, DE and BC with their alternates HL', DE' and BC'.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Thus the accumulator A can interact independently with any of the general purpose 8-bit registers in the alternate (or primed) register file, or, if HL' contains a pointer to memory, some byte there (DE' and BC' can also transfer 8-bit data between memory and accumulator A).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This can become confusing for programmers because after executing `EX AF,AF'` or `EXX`, the contents of the alternate (primed) registers are now in the main registers, and vice versa.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The only way for the programmer to understand and track this swapped condition is to trace through the code flow, noting each occurrence of a register swap instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Obviously if jump and call instructions are made within these code segments it can quickly become difficult to tell which register file is in context unless carefully commented.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Thus it is advisable that exchange instructions be used directly and in short discrete code segments.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Zilog Z280 instruction set includes `JAF` and `JAR` instructions which jump to a destination address if the alternate registers are in context (thus officially recognizing this programming complication).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] As on the 8080, 8-bit registers are typically paired to provide 16-bit versions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The *refresh register*, `R`, increments each time the CPU fetches an opcode (or an opcode prefix, which internally executes like a 1-byte instruction) and has no simple relationship with program execution.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This has sometimes been used to generate pseudorandom numbers in games, and also in software protection schemes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It has also been employed as a "hardware" counter in some designs; an example of this is the ZX81, which lets it keep track of character positions on the TV screen by triggering an interrupt at wrap around (by connecting INT to A6).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The *interrupt vector register*, `I`, is used for the Z80 specific mode 2 interrupts (selected by the `IM 2` instruction).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The pointer identifies a particular peripheral chip or peripheral function or event, where the chips are normally connected in a so-called daisy chain for priority resolution.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Like the refresh register, this register has also sometimes been used creatively; in interrupt modes 0 and 1 (or in a system not using interrupts) it can be used as simply another 8-bit data register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The instructions `LD A,R` and `LD A,I` affect the Z80 flags register, unlike all the other `LD` (load) instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Sign (bit 7) and Zero (bit 6) flags are set according to the data loaded from the Refresh or Interrupt source registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] For both instructions, the Parity/Overflow flag (bit 2) is set according to the current state of the IFF2 flip-flop.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Although the Z80 is generally considered an eight-bit CPU, it has a four-bit ALU, so calculations are done in two steps.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The first Intel 8008 assembly language was based on a simple (but systematic) syntax inherited from the Datapoint 2200 design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This original syntax was later transformed into a new, somewhat more traditional, assembly language form for this same original 8008 chip.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] At about the same time, the new assembly language was also extended to accommodate the additional addressing modes in the more advanced Intel 8080 chip (the 8008 and 8080 shared a language subset without being binary compatible; however, the 8008 was binary compatible with the Datapoint 2200).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In this process, the mnemonic `L`, for *LOAD*, was replaced by various abbreviations of the words *LOAD*, *STORE* and *MOVE*, intermixed with other symbolic letters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Because Intel claimed a copyright on their assembly mnemonics, a new assembly syntax had to be developed for the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] These principles made it straightforward to find names and forms for all new Z80 instructions, as well as orthogonalizations of old ones, such as `LD BC,1234`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] There was at least one inconsistency introduced.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Even though a subtract with carry is coded as `SBC A,r`, the non-carry subtract is coded as `SUB r` rather than `SUB A,r`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Apart from naming differences, and despite a certain discrepancy in basic register structure, the Z80 and 8086 syntax are virtually isomorphic for a large portion of instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Only quite superficial similarities (such as the word MOV, or the letter X, for extended register) exist between the 8080 and 8086 assembly languages, although 8080 programs can be translated to 8086 assembly language by translator programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This scheme gives the Z80 a large number of permutations of instructions and registers; Zilog categorizes these into 158 different "instruction types", 78 of which are the same as those of the Intel 8080 (allowing operation of all 8080 programs on a Z80).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] No explicit multiply instructions are available in the original Z80, though registers A and HL can be multiplied by powers of two with ADD A,A and ADD HL,HL instructions (similarly IX and IY also).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Shift instructions can also multiply or divide by powers of two.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Different sizes and variants of additions, shifts, and rotates have somewhat differing effects on flags because most of the flag-changing properties of the 8080 were copied.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, the parity flag bit P of the 8080 (bit 2) is called P/V (parity/overflow) in the Z80 as it serves the additional purpose of a twos complement overflow indicator, a feature lacking in the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Arithmetic instructions on the Z80 set it to indicate overflow rather than parity, while bitwise instructions still use it as a parity flag.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Also, bit 1 of the flags register (a spare bit on the 8080) is used as a flag N that indicates whether the last arithmetic instruction executed was a subtraction or addition.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 version of the `DAA` instruction (decimal adjust accumulator for BCD arithmetic) checks the N flag and behaves accordingly, so a (hypothetical) subtraction followed later by `DAA` will yield a different result on an old 8080 than on the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, this would likely be erroneous code on the 8080, as `DAA` was defined for addition only on that processor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 has six new `LD` instructions that can load the DE, BC, and SP register pairs from memory, and load memory from these three register pairs—unlike the 8080.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] As on the 8080, load instructions do not affect the flags (except for the special-purpose I and R register loads).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A result of a regular encoding (common with the 8080) is that each of the 8-bit registers can be loaded from themselves (e.g.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] New block transfer instructions can move up to 64 kilobytes from memory to memory or between memory and I/O peripheral ports.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Block instructions `LDIR` and `LDDR` (**l**oa**d**, **i**ncrement/**d**ecrement, **r**epeat) use HL to point to the source address, DE to the destination address, and BC as a byte counter.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Bytes are copied from source to destination, the pointers are incremented or decremented, and the byte counter is decremented until BC reaches zero.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Non-repeating versions `LDI` and `LDD` move a single byte and bump the pointers and byte counter, which if it becomes zero resets the P/V flag.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Corresponding memory-to-I/O instructions `INIR`, `INDR`, `OTIR`, `OTDR`, `INI`, `IND`, `OUTI` and `OUTD` operate similarly, except that B, not BC, is used as the byte counter.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 can input and output any register to an I/O port using register C to designate the port.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The last group of block instructions perform a `CP` compare operation between the byte at (HL) and the accumulator A.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The repeating versions `CPIR` and `CPDR` only terminate if BC goes to zero or a match is found.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] HL is left pointing to the byte after (`CPIR`) or before (`CPDR`) the matching byte.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] If no match is found, the Z flag is reset.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] There are non-repeating versions `CPI` and `CPD`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Unlike the 8080, the Z80 can jump to a relative address (`JR` instead of `JP`) using a shorter instruction with a signed 8-bit displacement.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] There are unconditional and conditional forms of this instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Only the zero and carry conditions can be tested.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] (All 8080 jumps and calls, conditional or not, are three-byte instructions.) If jump is taken, the two-byte `JR` instructions are slower than the 8080-style three-byte `JP` instructions; if not taken, `JR` instructions are quicker.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A two-byte instruction specialized for program looping is also new to the Z80: `DJNZ` (**d**ecrement **j**ump if **n**on-**z**ero) takes a signed 8-bit displacement as an operand.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The B register is decremented, and if the result is nonzero, then program execution jumps relative to PC; the flags remain unaltered.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] To perform an equivalent loop on an 8080 requires separate `DEC` and conditional jump (to a two-byte absolute address) instructions (totalling four bytes), and the `DEC` alters the flag register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Thus, for simple or linear accesses of data, use of IX and IY tend to be slower and occupy more memory.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Still, they may be useful in cases where the "main" registers are all occupied, by removing the need to save/restore registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Their officially undocumented 8-bit halves (see below) can be especially useful in this context, for they incur less slowdown than their 16-bit parents.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It was not uncommon for programmers to "poke" different offset displacement bytes (which were typically calculated dynamically) into indexed instructions; this is an example of self-modifying code, which was regular practice on nearly all early 8-bit processors with non-pipelined execution units.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The index registers have a parallel instruction to `JP (HL)`, which is `JP (IX)` and `JP (IY)`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This is often seen in stack-oriented languages like Forth, which at the end of every Forth word (atomic subroutines comprising the language) must jump unconditionally back to their thread interpreter routines.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Typically this jump instruction appears hundreds of times in an application, and using `JP (IX)` rather than `JP THREAD` saves a byte and two T-states for each occurrence.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This naturally makes the index register unavailable for any other use, or else the need to constantly reload it would negate its efficiency.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The 10-year-newer microcoded Z180 design could initially afford more "chip area", permitting a slightly more efficient implementation (using a wider ALU, among other things); similar things can be said for the Z800, Z280, and Z380.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, it was not until the fully pipelined eZ80 was launched in 2001 that those instructions finally became approximately as cycle-efficient as it is technically possible to make them, i.e. given the Z80 encodings combined with the capability to do an 8-bit read or write every clock cycle.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The index registers, IX and IY, were intended as flexible 16-bit pointers, enhancing the ability to manipulate memory, stack frames and data structures.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Officially, they were treated as 16-bit only.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In reality they were implemented as a pair of 8-bit registers, in the same fashion as the HL register, which is accessible either as 16 bits or separately as the *H*igh and *L*ow registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The binary opcodes (machine language) were identical, but preceded by a new opcode prefix.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Zilog published the opcodes and related mnemonics for the intended functions, but did not document the fact that every opcode that allowed manipulation of the H and L registers was equally valid for the 8 bit portions of the IX and IY registers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] For example, the opcode 26h followed by an immediate byte value `(LD H,n)` will load that value into the H register.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Preceding this two-byte instruction with the IX register's opcode prefix, DD, would instead result in the most significant 8 bits of the IX register being loaded with that same value.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A notable exception to this would be instructions similar to `LD H,(IX+d)` which make use of both the HL and IX or IY registers in the same instruction; in this case the DD prefix is only applied to the (IX+d) portion of the instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The halves of the XY registers could also hold operands for 8-bit arithmetic, logical and compare instructions, sparing the regular 8-bit registers for other use.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The undocumented ability to increment and decrement the upper half of an index register made it easy to expand the range of the normal indexed instructions, without having to resort to the documented `ADD/SBC XY,DE` or `ADD/SBC XY,BC`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] There are several other undocumented instructions as well.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Undocumented or illegal opcodes are not detected by the Z80 and have various effects, some of which are useful.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, as they are not part of the formal definition of the instruction set, different implementations of the Z80 are not guaranteed (or especially likely) to work the same way for every undocumented opcode.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The `OTDR` instruction does not conform to the Z80 documentation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Both the `OTDR` and `OTIR` instructions are supposed to leave the carry (C) flag unmodified.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The `OTIR` instruction operates correctly; however, during the execution of the `OTDR` instruction, the carry flag takes the results of a spurious compare between the accumulator (A) and the last output of the `OTDR` instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The following Z80 assembly source code is for a subroutine named `memcpy` that copies a block of data bytes of a given size from one location to another.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It demonstrates a variety of instructions but in practice it would not be coded this way as the Z80 has a single instruction that could replace this entire subroutine: `LDIR`.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The sample code will move one byte every 46 T-states.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Substituting the `LDIR` instruction will move each byte in only 21 T-states.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Note that the assembled code is binary-compatible with the Intel 8080 and 8085 CPUs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Each instruction is executed in steps that are usually termed machine cycles (M-cycles), each of which can take between three and six clock periods (T-states).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Each M-cycle corresponds roughly to one memory access or internal operation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Multiple instructions actually end during the M1 of the *next* instruction which is known as a *fetch/execute overlap*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 machine cycles are sequenced by an internal state machine which builds each M-cycle out of 3, 4, 5 or 6 T-states depending on context.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This avoids cumbersome asynchronous logic and makes the control signals behave consistently at a wide range of clock frequencies.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It also means that a higher frequency crystal must be used than without this subdivision of machine cycles (approximately 2–3 times higher).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] It does not imply tighter requirements on memory access times, since a high resolution clock allows more precise control of memory timings and so memory can be active in parallel with the CPU to a greater extent, allowing more efficient use of available memory bandwidth.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] One central example of this is that, for opcode fetch, the Z80 combines two full clock cycles into a memory access period (the M1-signal).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] In the Z80 this signal lasts for a relatively larger part of the typical instruction execution time than in a design such as the 6800, 6502, or similar, where this period would typically last typically 30-40% of a clock cycle.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] With memory chip affordability (i.e. access times around 450-250 ns in the 1980s) typically determining the fastest possible access time, this meant that such designs were locked to a significantly longer clock cycle (i.e. lower internal clock speed) than the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Memory was generally slow compared to the state machine sub-cycles (clock cycles) used in contemporary microprocessors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The shortest machine cycle that could safely be used in embedded designs has therefore often been limited by memory access times, not by the maximum CPU frequency (especially so during the home computer era).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] However, this relation has slowly changed during the last decades, particularly regarding SRAM; cacheless, single-cycle designs such as the eZ80 have therefore become much more meaningful recently.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The content of the refresh register R is sent out on the lower half of the address bus along with a refresh control signal while the CPU is decoding and executing the fetched instruction.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] During refresh the contents of the Interrupt register I are sent out on the upper half of the address bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Zilog introduced a number of peripheral parts for the Z80, which all support the Z80's interrupt handling system and I/O address space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] These include the counter/timer channel (CTC), the SIO (serial input/output), the DMA (direct memory access), the PIO (parallel input/output) and the DART (dual asynchronous receiver–transmitter).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] As the product line developed, low-power, high-speed and CMOS versions of these chips were introduced.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Like the 8080, 8085 and 8086 processors, but unlike processors such as the Motorola 6800 and MOS Technology 6502, the Z80 and 8080 has a separate control line and address space for I/O instructions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] While some Z80-based computers such as the Osborne 1 used "Motorola-style" memory mapped input/output devices, usually the I/O space was used to address one of the Zilog peripheral chips compatible with the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] During the timing for an I/O read or an I/O write operation, a single wait cycle is automatically inserted by the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] Zilog I/O chips supported the Z80's new mode 2 interrupts which simplified interrupt handling for large numbers of peripherals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] The Z80 was officially described as supporting 16-bit (64 KB) memory addressing, and 8-bit (256 ports) I/O-addressing.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] All I/O instructions actually assert the entire 16-bit address bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] OUT (C),reg and IN reg,(C) places the contents of the entire 16-bit BC register on the address bus; OUT (n),A and IN A,(n) places the contents of the A register on b8–b15 of the address bus and the port address *n* on b0–b7 of the address bus.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] A designer could choose to decode the entire 16-bit address bus on I/O operations in order to take advantage of this feature, or use the high half of the address bus to select subfeatures of the I/O device.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p01] This feature has also been used to minimise decoding hardware requirements, such as in the Amstrad CPC/PCW and ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Mostek, which produced the first Z80 for Zilog, offered it second-source as MK3880.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] SGS-Thomson (now STMicroelectronics) was a second source, too, with their Z8400.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Sharp and NEC developed second sources for the NMOS Z80, the LH0080 and μPD780C, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The LH0080 was used in various home computers and personal computers made by Sharp and other Japanese manufacturers, including Sony MSX computers, and a number of computers in the Sharp MZ series.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Sharp developed the LH0080A and LH0080B to operate at frequencies of 4 MHz and 6 MHz, respectively.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Sharp also developed LH0083 compatible with Z80 DMA.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Toshiba made a CMOS-version, the TMPZ84C00, which is believed (but not verified) to be the same design also used by Zilog for its own CMOS Z84C00.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] There were also Z8400, Z80-chips made by GoldStar (now LG) and the BU18400 series of Z80-clones (including DMA, PIO, CTC, DART and SIO) in NMOS and CMOS made by ROHM Electronics.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The LH5080, LH5081, and LH5082, which are CMOS versions of the Z80, PIO, and CTC respectively, are manufactured by Sharp.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In East Germany, an unlicensed clone of the Z80, known as the U880, was manufactured.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] It was used extensively in Robotron's and VEB Mikroelektronik Mühlhausen's computer systems (such as the KC85-series) and also in multiple self-made computer systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In Romania another unlicensed clone could be found, named MMN80CPU and produced by Microelectronica, used in home computers like TIM-S, HC, COBRA.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Also, several clones of Z80 were created in the Soviet Union, notable ones being the T34BM1, also called КР1858ВМ1 (parallelling the Soviet 8080-clone KR580VM80A).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The first marking was used in pre-production series, while the second had to be used for a larger production.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Though, due to the collapse of Soviet microelectronics in the late 1980s, there are more T34BM1s than КР1858ВМ1s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, the Z80 was used in a great number of fairly anonymous business-oriented machines with the CP/M operating system, a combination that dominated the market at the time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Four well-known examples of Z80 business computers running CP/M are the Heathkit H89, the portable Osborne 1, the Kaypro series, and the Epson QX-10.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Less well-known was the expensive high-end Otrona Attache.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Some systems used multi-tasking operating system software (like MP/M or Morrow's Micronix) to share the one processor between several concurrent users.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Multiple home computers were introduced that used the Z80 as the main processor or as a plug-in option to allow access to software written for the Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Notable are the TRS-80 series, including the original model (later retronymed "Model I"), Model II, Model III, and Model 4, which were equipped with a Z80 as their main processor, and some (but not all) other TRS-80 models which used the Z80 as either the main or a secondary processor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Other notable machines were the DEC Rainbow 100, and the Seequa Chameleon, both of which featured both an Intel 8088 and a Z80 CPU, to support either 8-bit CP/M-80 applications running on the Z80, or a custom MS-DOS that was not fully compatible with PC DOS applications running on the 8088.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In 1981, Multitech (later to become Acer) introduced the Microprofessor I, a simple and inexpensive training system for the Z80 microprocessor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Currently, it is still manufactured and sold by Flite Electronics International Limited in Southampton, England.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In 1984 Toshiba introduced the Toshiba MSX HX-10 in Japan and Australia.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In 1985, Sharp introduced the Hotbit and Gradiente introduced the Expert, which became the dominant 8-bit home computers in Brazil until the late 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Use of the Z80 in lighter, battery-operated devices became more widespread with the availability of CMOS versions of the processor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] It also inspired the development of other CMOS based processors, such as the LH5801 from Sharp.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Sharp PC-1500, a BASIC-programmable pocket computer was released in 1981, followed by the improved Sharp PC-1600 in 1986 and the Sharp PC-E220 in 1991.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Later models of the Sharp Wizard series of personal organizers also were Z80 based.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Laptops which could run the CP/M operating system just like the desktop machines followed with Epson PX-8 Geneva in 1984, and in 1985 the Epson PX-4 and Bondwell-2.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] While the laptop market in subsequent years moved to more powerful Intel 8086 processors and the MS-DOS operating system, light-weight Z80-based systems with a longer battery life were still being introduced, such as the Cambridge Z88 in 1988 and the Amstrad NC100 in 1992.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Z80-derived Z8S180 also found its way into an early pen-operated personal digital assistant, the Amstrad PenPad PDA600 in 1993.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Hong Kong-based VTech produced a line of small laptop computers called "Lasers" based on a Z80.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The last two were the Laser PC5 and PC6.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Cidco MailStation Mivo 100, first released in 1999, was a stand-alone portable email device, with a Z80-based microcontroller.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Texas Instruments produced a line of pocket organizers (ending in 2000) using Toshiba processors built around a Z80 core; the first of these was the TI PS-6200 and after a lengthy production run of some dozen models culminated in their PocketMate series.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Zilog Z80 has long been a popular microprocessor in embedded systems and microcontroller cores, where it remains in widespread use today.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Applications of the Z80 include uses in consumer electronics, industrial products, and electronic musical instruments.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] For example, Z80 was used in the groundbreaking music synthesizer Prophet-5, as well as in the first MIDI-equipped synthesizer, the Prophet 600.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Z80 was the basis for all E-mu Systems instruments from 1976 to 1986.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Casio used the Z80A in its PV-1000 video game console.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Many early-1980s arcade video games, including the arcade game Pac-Man, contain Z80 CPUs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The Z80 was used in Sega's Master System and Game Gear consoles.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Z80 CPUs were also used in the popular TI-8x series of graphing calculators from Texas Instruments, beginning in 1990 with the TI-81, which features a Z80 clocked at 2 MHz.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Most higher-line calculators in the series, starting with the TI-82 and TI-85, clock their Z80 CPUs at 6 MHz or higher.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] (A few models with TI-8x names use other CPUs, such as the M68000, but the vast majority are Z80-based.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] TI-83 and TI-84 Plus model graphing calculators uses the Z80 while the TI-84 Plus CE series use the eZ80; all three calculator series are still sold by Texas Instruments as of 2025.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In the late 1980s, a series of Soviet landline phones called "AON" featured the Z80; these phones expanded the feature set of the landline with caller ID, different ringtones based on the caller, speed dial and so forth.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] In the second half of the 1990s however, manufacturers of these phones switched to 8051 compatible MCUs to reduce power consumption, and prevent compact wall power adapters from overheating.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Early Micromouse autonomous maze-solving mobile robots used the Z80 CPU, such as the Moonlight Special (1978), that utilized a 4 MHz Z80A to minimize onboard hardware by leveraging its single +5V power supply requirement.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The design relied on the processor's new block transfer instructions to manage maze node tables and its vectored interrupts to handle real-time sensor sampling and stepper motor control within a tight 4 kHz (250 µsec) interrupt cycle.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] On April 15, 2024, Zilog announced the discontinuation of the Z80 processor, with orders being accepted until June 14, 2024.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] The announcement included 13 variants of the Z80 processor, some of which were DIP40 variants of the chip.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zilog-z80-p02] Zilog will continue to manufacture the upgraded eZ80 version of the processor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The **ZX Spectrum** (UK: /zɛd ɛks/) is an 8-bit home computer developed and marketed by Sinclair Research.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Spectrum played a pivotal role in the history of personal computers and video games, especially in the United Kingdom.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was one of the all-time bestselling British computers with over five million units sold.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was first released in Britain on 23 April 1982 with releases in some other regions, including West Germany and the United States, after that year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The machine was designed by the English entrepreneur and inventor Sir Clive Sinclair and his small team in Cambridge, and was manufactured in Dundee, Scotland by Timex Corporation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was made to be small, simple, and most importantly inexpensive, with as few components as possible.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The addendum "Spectrum" was chosen to highlight the machine's colour display, which differed from the black-and-white display of its predecessor, the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Rick Dickinson designed its distinctive case, rainbow motif, and rubber keyboard.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Video output is transmitted to a television set rather than a dedicated monitor, while application software is loaded and saved onto compact audio cassettes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum was initially distributed by mail order, but after severe backlogs it was sold through High Street chains in the United Kingdom.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was released in the US as the Timex Sinclair 2068 in 1983, and in some parts of Europe as the Timex Computer 2048.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] There are seven models overall, ranging from the entry level with 16 KB RAM released in 1982 to the ZX Spectrum +3 with 128 KB RAM and built-in floppy disk drive in 1987.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The machine primarily competed with the Commodore 64, BBC Micro, Dragon 32, and the Amstrad CPC range.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Over 24,000 software products were released for the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Its introduction led to a boom in companies producing software and hardware, the effects of which are still seen.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was among the first home computers aimed at a mainstream UK audience, with some crediting it for launching the British information technology industry.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Spectrum was Britain's top-selling computer until the Amstrad PCW surpassed it in the 1990s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum was conceived and designed by engineers at Sinclair Research, founded by English entrepreneur and inventor Clive Sinclair, who was well known for his eccentricity and pioneering ethic.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] On 25 July 1961, three years after passing his A-levels, he founded Sinclair Radionics to advertise his inventions and buy components.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In 1972, Sinclair competed with Texas Instruments to produce the world's first pocket calculator, the Sinclair Executive.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By the mid 1970s, Sinclair Radionics was producing handheld electronic calculators, miniature televisions, and the ill-fated digital Black Watch wristwatch.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Due to financial losses, Sinclair sought investors from the National Enterprise Board (NEB), who had bought a 43% interest in the company and streamlined his product line.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair's relationship with the NEB had worsened, and by 1979 it opted to break up Sinclair Radionics entirely, selling off its television division to Binatone and its calculator division to ESL Bristol.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] After incurring a £7 million investment loss, Sinclair was given a golden handshake and an estimated £10,000 severance package.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] He had a former employee, Christopher Curry, establish a "corporate lifeboat" company named Science of Cambridge Ltd, in July 1977, called such as they were located near the University of Cambridge.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By this time inexpensive microprocessors had started appearing on the market, which prompted Sinclair to start producing the MK14, a computer teaching kit which sold well at a very low price.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Encouraged by this success, Sinclair renamed his company to Sinclair Research, and started looking to manufacture personal computers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Keeping the cost low was essential for Sinclair to avoid his products from becoming outpriced by American or Japanese equivalents as had happened to several of the previous Sinclair Radionics products.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] On 29 January 1980, the ZX80 home computer was launched to immediate popularity; notable for being one of the first computers available in the United Kingdom for less than £100.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The company conducted no market research whatsoever prior to the launch of the ZX80; according to Sinclair, he "simply had a hunch" that the public was sufficiently interested to make such a project feasible and went ahead with ordering 100,000 sets of parts so that he could launch at high volume.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] On 5 March 1981, the ZX81 was launched worldwide to immense success with more than 1.5 million units sold, 60% of which was outside Britain.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] According to Ben Rosen, by pricing the ZX81 so low, the company had "opened up a completely new market among people who had never previously considered owning a computer".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] After its release, computing in Britain became an activity for the general public rather than the preserve of office workers and hobbyists.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX81's commercial success made Sinclair Research one of Britain's leading computer manufacturers, with Sinclair himself reportedly "amused and gratified" by the attention the machine received.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Development of the ZX Spectrum began in September 1981, a few months after the release of the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair resolved to make his own products obsolete before his rivals developed the products that would do so.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Parts of designs from the ZX80 and ZX81 were reused to ensure a speedy and cost-effective manufacturing process.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The team consisted of 20 engineers housed in a small office at 6 King's Parade, Cambridge.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] During early production, the machine was known as the ZX81 Colour or the ZX82 to highlight the machine's colour display, which differed from the black and white of its predecessors.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The addendum "Spectrum" was added later on, to emphasise its 15-colour palette.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Aside from a new crystal oscillator and extra chips to add additional kilobytes of memory, the ZX Spectrum was intended to be, as quoted by Sinclair's marketing manager, essentially a "ZX81 with colour".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] According to Sinclair, the team also wanted to combine the ZX81's separate random-access memory sections for audio and video into a single bank.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Chief engineer Richard Altwasser was responsible for the ZX Spectrum's hardware design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] His main contribution was the design of the semi-custom uncommitted logic array (ULA) integrated circuit, which integrated, on a single chip, the essential hardware functions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Altwasser designed a graphics mode that required less than 7 kilobytes of memory and implemented it on the ULA.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Lengthy discussions between Altwasser and Sinclair engineers resulted in a broad agreement that the ZX Spectrum must have high-resolution graphics, 16 kilobytes of memory, an improved cassette interface, and an impressive colour palette.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To achieve this, the team had to divorce the central processing unit (CPU) away from the main display to enable it to work at full efficiency – a method which contrasted with the ZX81's integrated CPU.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The inclusion of colour proved a major obstacle to the engineers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] A Teletext-like approach was briefly considered, in which each line of text would have colour-change codes inserted into it.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This was deemed unsuitable for high-resolution graphs or diagrams that involved multiple colour changes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Altwasser devised the idea of allocating a colour attribute to each character position on the screen.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This ultimately used eight bits of memory for each character position; three bits to provide any one of eight foreground colours and three bits for the eight background colours, one bit for extra brightness and one bit for flashing.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Overall, the system took up slightly less than 7 kilobytes of memory, leaving an additional 9 kilobytes to write programs – a figure that pleased the team.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Much of the firmware was written by computer scientist Steve Vickers from Nine Tiles, who compiled all control routines to produce the Sinclair BASIC interpreter, a custom variant of the general purpose BASIC programming language.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Making a custom interpreter made it possible to fit all of its functionality into a very small amount of read-only memory (ROM).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The development process of the software was marked by disagreements between Nine Tiles and Sinclair Research.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair placed an emphasis on expediting the release of the Spectrum, primarily by minimising alterations in the software from the ZX81, which had in turn been based on the ZX80's software.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The software architecture of the ZX80, however, had been tailored for a severely constrained memory system, and in Nine Tiles' opinion was unsuitable for the enhanced processing demands of the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair favoured solving this with expansion modules on the existing framework like with the ZX81, which Nine Tiles disagreed with.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Ultimately, both designs were developed, but Vickers and Nine Tiles were unable to finish their version before the launch of the Spectrum and it was not used.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The distinctive case and colourful design of the ZX Spectrum was the creation of Rick Dickinson, a young British industrial designer who had been hired by Sinclair to design the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Dickinson was tasked to design a sleeker and more "marketable" appearance to the new machine, whilst ensuring all 192 BASIC functions could fit onto 40 physical keys.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Early sketches from August 1981 showed the case was to be more angular and wedge-like, in similar vein to an upgraded ZX81 model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Dickinson later settled on a flatter design with a raised rear section and rounded sides in order to depict the machine as "more advanced" as opposed to a mere upgrade.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In drawing up potential logos, Dickinson proposed a series of different logotypes which all featured rainbow slashes across the keyboard.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The design of the Spectrum's rubber keyboard was simplified from several hundred components to a conventional moving keyboard down to "four to five" moving parts using a new technology.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The keyboard was still undergoing changes as late as February 1982; some sketches included a roundel-on-square key design which was later featured on the later Spectrum+ model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Dickinson recalled in 2007 that "everything was cost driven" and that the minimalist, Bauhaus approach to the Spectrum gave it an elegant yet "[non] revolutionary" form.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The drawing board on which Dickinson designed the ZX Spectrum is now on display in the Science Museum in London.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The need for an improved cassette interface was apparent from ZX81 users who encountered problems trying to save and load programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To increase the data transfer speed, the team decreased the length of tones that represent binary data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Originally, the team aimed for 1000 baud, but succeeded in reaching a considerably faster 1500 baud.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To increase reliability, a leading period of constant tone was introduced, allowing the cassette recorder's automatic gain control to settle down, eliminating hisses on the tape.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] A Schmitt trigger was added inside the ULA to reduce noise of the received signal.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Unlike the ZX81, the Spectrum is able to maintain its display during data transfer, allowing programs to show a splash screen whilst loading.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] As with the ZX81, the ZX Spectrum was manufactured in Dundee, Scotland, by Timex Corporation at the Dryburgh factory.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Prior to the ZX81, Timex was an established manufacturer of mechanical watches, but had little experience in assembling electronics.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Timex's director, Fred Olsen, determined that the company would diversify into other areas and signed a contract with Sinclair.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum was officially revealed before journalists by Sinclair at the Churchill Hotel in Marylebone, London, on 23 April 1982.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Later that week, the machine was presented in a "blaze of publicity" at the Earl's Court Computer Show in London, and the ZX Microfair in Manchester.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum was launched with two models: a 16KB 'basic' version, and an enhanced 48KB variant.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The former model had an undercutting price of £125, significantly lower than its main competitor the BBC Micro, whilst the latter model's price of £175 was comparable to a third of an Apple II computer.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Upon release, the keyboard surprised many users due to its use of rubber keys, described as offering the feel of "dead flesh".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair himself remarked that the keyboard's rubber mould was "unusual", but consumers were undeterred.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Despite very high demand, Sinclair Research was "notoriously late" in delivering the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Their practice of offering mail-order sales before units were ready ensured a constant cash flow, but meant a lacking distribution.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Nigel Searle, the newly-appointed chief of Sinclair's computer division, said in June 1982 the company had no plans to stock the new machine in WHSmith, which was at the time Sinclair's only retailer.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Searle explained that the mail-order system was in place due to there being no "obvious" retail outlets in the United Kingdom which could sell personal computers, and it made "better sense" financially to continue selling through mail-order.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The company's conservative approach to distributing the machine was criticised, with disillusioned customers telephoning and writing letters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Demand sky-rocketed beyond Sinclair's planned 20,000 monthly unit output to a backlog of 30,000 orders by July 1982.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Due to a scheduled holiday at the Timex factory that summer, the backlog had risen to 40,000 units.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair issued a public apology in September that year, and promised that the backlog would be cleared by the end of that month.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Supply did not return to normal until the 1982 Christmas season.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Production of the machine rapidly increased with the arrival of the less expensive Issue 2 motherboard, a redesign of the main circuit board which addressed hardware manufacturing defects that affected production of the first model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sales of the ZX Spectrum reached 200,000 in its first nine months, rising to 300,000 for the whole of the first year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By August 1983 total sales in Britain and Europe had exceeded 500,000, with the millionth Spectrum manufactured on 9 December 1983.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By this point, an average of 50,000 units were being purchased each month.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In July 1983, an enhanced version of the ZX Spectrum was launched in the United States as the Timex Sinclair 2068.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Advertisements described it as having 72 kilobytes of memory and a full range of colour and sound for under $200.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Despite the improvements upon its British counterpart, sales were poor and Timex Sinclair collapsed the following year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] A crucial part of the company's marketing strategy was to implement regular price-cutting at strategic intervals to maintain market share.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Ian Adamson and Richard Kennedy noted that Sinclair's method was driven by securing his leading position through "panicking" the competition.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] While most companies at the time reduced prices of their products while their market share was dwindling, Sinclair Research discounted theirs shortly after sales had peaked, throwing the competition into "utter disarray".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair Research made a profit of £14 million in 1983, compared to £8.5 million the previous year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Turnover doubled from £27.2 million to £54.5 million, which equated to roughly £1 million for each person employed directly by the company.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Clive Sinclair became a focal point during the ZX Spectrum's marketing campaign by putting a human face onto the business.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair Research was portrayed in the media as a "plucky" British challenger taking on the technical and marketing might of giant American and Japanese corporations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The press praised Sinclair as a visionary genius, with *The Sun* lauding him as "the most prodigious inventor since Leonardo da Vinci".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Adamson and Kennedy wrote that Sinclair outgrew the role of microcomputer manufacturer and "accepted the mantle of pioneering boffin leading Britain into a technological utopia".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair's contribution to the technology sector resulted in him being knighted upon the recommendation of Margaret Thatcher in the Queen's 1983 Birthday Honours List.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The United Kingdom was largely immunised from the effects of the video game crash of 1983, due to the saturation of home computers such as the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The microcomputer market continued to grow and game development was unhindered despite the turbulence in the American markets.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Computer games remained the dominant sector of the British home video game market up until they were surpassed by Sega and Nintendo consoles in 1991.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By the end of 1983 there were more than 450 companies in Britain selling video games on cassette, compared to 95 the year before.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] An estimated 10,000 to 50,000 people, mostly young men, were developing games out of their homes based on advertisements in popular magazines.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The growth of video games during this period has been compared to the punk subculture, fuelled by young people making money from their games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By the mid 1980s, Sinclair Research's share of the British home computer market had climbed to a high of 40 per cent.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sales in the 1984 Christmas season were described as "extremely good".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In early 1985 the British press reported the home computer boom to have ended, leaving many companies slashing prices of their hardware to anticipate lower sales.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Despite this, celebration of Sinclair's success in the computing market continued at the *Which Computer?* show in Birmingham, where the five-millionth Sinclair machine (a gold coloured QL) was issued as a prize.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum's successor, the Sinclair QL, was officially announced on 12 January 1984, shortly before the Macintosh 128K went on sale.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Contrasting with its predecessors, the QL was aimed at more serious, professional home users.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Fully operational QLs were not available until the late summer, and complaints against Sinclair concerning delays were upheld by the Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) in May of that year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Particularly serious were allegations that Sinclair was cashing cheques months before machines were shipped.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By autumn 1984, Sinclair was still publicly forecasting that it would be a "million seller" and that 250,000 units would be sold by the end of the year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] QL production was suspended in February 1985, and the price was halved by the end of the year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It ultimately flopped, with 139,454 units being manufactured.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum+, a rebranded ZX Spectrum with identical technical specifications except for the QL-like keyboard, was introduced in October 1984 and made available in WHSmith's stores the day after its launch.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Retailers stocked the device in high quantities, anticipating robust Christmas sales.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It did not perform as well as projected, leading to a significant drop in Sinclair's income from orders in January, as retailers were left with surplus stock.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] An upgraded model, the ZX Spectrum 128, was released in Spain in September 1985, financed by the Spanish distributor Investrónica.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The UK launch was postponed until January 1986 due to the substantial leftover inventory of the prior model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] While the Sinclair QL was in development, Sinclair also hoped to repeat his success with the Spectrum in the fledgling electric vehicle market, which he saw as ripe for a new approach.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] On 10 January 1985, Sinclair unveiled the Sinclair C5, a small one-person battery electric recumbent tricycle.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It marked the culmination of Sir Clive's long-running interest in electric vehicles.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The C5 turned out to be a significant commercial failure, selling only 17,000 units and losing Sinclair £7 million.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It has since been described as "one of the great marketing bombs of postwar British industry".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ASA ordered Sinclair to withdraw advertisements for the C5 after finding that the company's claims about its safety could not be justified.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The combined failures of the C5 and QL caused investors to lose confidence in Sinclair's judgement.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In May 1985, Sinclair Research announced their intention to raise an additional £10 to £15 million to restructure the organisation, but securing the funds proved challenging.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In June 1985, business magnate Robert Maxwell disclosed a takeover bid for Sinclair Research through Hollis Brothers, a subsidiary of his Pergamon Press.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] However, the deal was terminated in August 1985.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] On 7 April 1986 the company sold their entire computer product range, along with the "Sinclair" brand name, to Alan Sugar's Amstrad for £5 million.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The takeover sent ripples through the London Stock Exchange, but Amstrad's shares soon recovered, with one stock broker affirming that "the City appears to have taken the news in its stride".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Amstrad's acquisition saw the release of three improved ZX Spectrum models throughout the late 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By 1990, Sinclair Research consisted of Sinclair and two other employees down from 130 employees at its peak in 1985.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum was officially discontinued in 1992, after ten years on the market.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The central processing unit is a Zilog Z80, an 8-bit microprocessor, with a clock rate of 3.5 MHz.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The original model Spectrum has 16 KB of ROM and either 16 KB or 48 KB of RAM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Video output is channelled through an RF modulator, intended for use with contemporary television sets.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Text is displayed using a grid of 32 columns × 24 rows of characters from the ZX Spectrum character set, or from a custom set.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] There is a colour palette of 15 colours: seven saturated colours at two levels of brightness and black.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The image resolution is 256 × 192 pixels, subject to the same colour limitations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Colour is stored separately from the pixel bitmap in a 32 × 24 grid corresponding to the character cells.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This means that all pixels within an 8 × 8 character block share one foreground colour and one background colour.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Altwasser received a patent for this design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] An "attribute" consists of a foreground and a background colour, a brightness level (normal or bright) and a flashing "flag" which causes the two colours to swap at regular intervals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This scheme leads to what is dubbed attribute clash, where a desired colour of a specific pixel cannot be selected, but only the colour attributes of an 8 × 8 block.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This became a distinctive feature of the Spectrum, requiring games and other programs to be designed with this limitation in mind.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Other machines, such as the Amstrad CPC and Commodore 64, do not suffer from this limitation.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] While the C64 also uses colour attributes, it has a special multicolour mode and hardware sprites which do not involve attribute clash.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sound is produced through a single-channel beeper capable of generating ten octaves.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sounds are generated by toggling a single bit on and off.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] From BASIC, the BEEP command plays sounds of specified pitch and duration.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The processor is occupied exclusively with BEEP until the sound completes, limiting concurrent operations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Despite these constraints, it was a significant step forward from the silence of the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Programmers devised workarounds and explored unconventional methods such as programming the beeper to emit multiple pitches.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Later software allows for two-channel sound playback.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The machine includes an expansion bus edge connector and 3.5 mm audio in/out ports, for connecting a cassette recorder to load and save programs and data.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The EAR port has a higher output than the MIC and is recommended for headphones, while the MIC port is intended for attachment to other audio devices as a line-in source.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The machine's Sinclair BASIC interpreter is stored in 16 KiB ROM, along with essential system routines.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ROM code, responsible for tasks such as floating point calculations and expression parsing, exhibited significant similarities to ZX81, although a few outdated routines remained in the Spectrum ROM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Spectrum's keyboard is imprinted with BASIC keywords.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To input a command in BASIC, many keywords require a single keyboard stroke.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Other keywords require a change of keyboard mode by a few keystrokes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The BASIC interpreter is derived from the one used on the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] A BASIC program for ZX81 can be entered into a ZX Spectrum with minimal modifications.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] However, Spectrum BASIC introduced numerous additional features, enhancing its usability.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum character set was expanded compared to that of the ZX81, which lacked lowercase letters.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Spectrum BASIC incorporated extra keywords for better graphics and sound functionality, and support for multi-statement lines was added.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The built-in ROM tape modulation software routines for cassette data storage enable data transfers at an average speed of 171 bytes per second, with a theoretical peak speed of 256 bytes/s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The tape modulation is significantly more advanced than the ZX81, with approximately four times faster average speeds.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The original ZX Spectrum is remembered for its rubber chiclet keyboard, diminutive size and distinctive rainbow motif.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was originally released on 23 April 1982 with 16 KB of RAM for £125 (equivalent to £446 in 2025) or with 48 KB for £175 (equivalent to £624 in 2025); these prices were reduced to £99 (equivalent to £337 in 2025) and £129 (equivalent to £439 in 2025) respectively in 1983.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Owners of the 16 KB model could purchase an internal 32 KB RAM upgrade, which for early "Issue 1" machines consisted of a daughterboard.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Later issue machines required the fitting of 8 dynamic RAM chips and a few TTL chips.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Users could mail their 16K Spectrums to Sinclair to be upgraded to 48 KB versions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Later revisions contained 64 KB of memory but were configured such that only 48 KB were usable.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] External 32 KB RAM packs that mounted in the rear expansion slot were available from third parties.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] An "Issue 1" ZX Spectrum can be distinguished from Issue 2 or 3 models by the colour of the keys – light grey for Issue 1, blue-grey for later machines.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Although the official service manual states that approximately 26,000 of these original boards were manufactured, subsequent serial number analysis shows that only 16,000 were produced, almost all of which fell in the serial number range 001-000001 to 001-016000.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] An online tool now exists to allow users to ascertain the likely issue number of their ZX Spectrum by inputting the serial number.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] These models experienced numerous changes to its motherboard design throughout its life; mainly to improve manufacturing efficiencies, but also to correct bugs from previous boards.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Another issue was with the Spectrum's power supply.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In March 1983, Sinclair issued an urgent product recall warning for all owners of models bought after 1 January 1983.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Plugs with a non-textured surface were at risk of causing shock, and were asked to be sent back to a warehouse in Cambridgeshire which would supply a replacement within 48 hours.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Development of the *ZX Spectrum+* began in June 1984, and was released on 15 October that year at £179.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was assembled by AB Electronics in South Wales and Samsung in South Korea.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This 48 KB Spectrum introduced a new QL-style case with an injection-moulded keyboard and a reset button that functions as a switch shorting across the CPU reset capacitor.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Electronically, it was identical to the previous 48 KB model, and motherboards could be removed from original Spectrums and placed in the Spectrum+ case.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] These cases were sold to the public as a DIY upgrade.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Some retailers reported a failure rate of up to 30%, compared with a more typical 5–6% for the older model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In early 1985, the original Spectrum was officially discontinued, and the ZX Spectrum+ was reduced in price to £129.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In 1985, Sinclair developed the ZX Spectrum 128 (codenamed *Derby*) in conjunction with their Spanish distributor Investrónica (a subsidiary of El Corte Inglés department store group).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Investrónica had helped adapt the ZX Spectrum+ to the Spanish market after their government introduced a special tax on all computers with 64 KB RAM or less, and a law which obliged all computers sold in Spain to support the Spanish alphabet and show messages in Spanish.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The appearance of the ZX Spectrum 128 is similar to the ZX Spectrum+, with the addition of a large external heatsink for the internal 7805 voltage regulator to the right-hand end of the case, replacing the internal heatsink in previous versions.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This external heatsink led to the system's nickname, "The Toast Rack".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] New features included 128 KB RAM with RAM disc commands, three-channel audio via the AY-3-8912 chip, MIDI compatibility, an RS-232 serial port, an RGB monitor port, 32 KB of ROM including an improved BASIC editor, and an external keypad.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The machine was simultaneously unveiled for the first time and launched in September 1985 at the SIMO '85 trade show in Spain, with a price of 44,250 pesetas.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair later presented the ZX Spectrum 128 at The May Fair Hotel's Crystal Rooms in London, where he acknowledged that entertainment was the most common use of home computers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Due to the large number of unsold Spectrum+ models, Sinclair decided not to start it selling in the United Kingdom until January 1986 at a price of £179.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Zilog Z80 processor used in the Spectrum has a 16-bit address bus, which means only 64 KB of memory can be directly addressed.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To facilitate the extra 80 KB of RAM the designers used bank switching so the new memory would be available as eight pages of 16 KB at the top of the address space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The same technique was used to page between the new 16 KB editor ROM and the original 16 KB BASIC ROM at the bottom of the address space.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The new sound chip and MIDI out abilities were exposed to the BASIC programming language with the command `PLAY` and a new command `SPECTRUM` was added to switch the machine into 48K mode, keeping the current BASIC program intact (although there is no command to switch back to 128K mode).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] To enable BASIC programmers to access the additional memory, a RAM disk was created where files could be stored in the additional 80 KB of RAM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The new commands took the place of two existing user-defined-character spaces causing compatibility problems with certain BASIC programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Unlike its predecessors, it has no internal speaker, and can only produce sound from a television speaker.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum +2 marked Amstrad's entry into the Spectrum market shortly after their acquisition of the Spectrum range and "Sinclair" brand in 1986.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It has a grey case with a spring-loaded keyboard, dual joystick ports, and an integrated cassette recorder known as the "Datacorder" (akin to the Amstrad CPC 464).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The boot-up message reads "© 1986 Amstrad".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It is largely identical to the ZX Spectrum 128 in most technical aspects.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The new keyboard does not have the BASIC keyword markings of earlier Spectrums, except for `LOAD`, `CODE`, and `RUN` markings.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Instead, the +2 has a menu system, almost identical to that of the ZX Spectrum 128, allowing users to switch between 48K BASIC programming with keywords and 128K BASIC programming, where all words, both keywords and others, need to be typed out in full.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Despite these changes, the layout remained identical to that of the 128.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum +3, launched in 1987, replaces the cassette drive with a built-in 3-inch floppy disk.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Initially £249, it later retailed for £199.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It is the only Spectrum model capable of running the CP/M operating system without additional hardware.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Unlike its predecessors, the ZX Spectrum +3 power supply uses a DIN connector.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Significant alterations caused a series of incompatibilities.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The removal of several lines on the expansion bus edge connector caused complications for some peripherals.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Additionally, changes in memory timing led to certain RAM banks being contended, causing failures in high-speed colour-changing effects.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The keypad scanning routines from the ROM were also eliminated, so some older 48K and 128K games no longer worked.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Interface 1 was also incompatible because of disparities in ROM and expansion connectors, making it impossible to connect and use the Microdrive units.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Production of the +3 was discontinued in December 1990, reportedly in response to Amstrad's relaunch of their CPC range, with an estimated 15% of ZX Spectrums sold being +3 models at the time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The +2B model, the only other model still in production at this point, continued to be manufactured, as it was believed not to be in direct competition with other computers in Amstrad's product range.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum +2A was a new version of the Spectrum +2 using the same circuit board as the Spectrum +3.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was sold from late 1988 and unlike the original grey +2 is housed in a black case.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The six datacorder buttons are blank on the black +2A/B with the function graphics (play, pause, eject etc.) being printed above them on the case, whereas the graphics are directly on the datacorder buttons of the grey +2.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Spectrum +2A/+3 motherboard (AMSTRAD part number Z70830) was designed so that it could be assembled with a +2 style "datacorder" connected instead of the floppy disk controller.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The power supply of the ZX Spectrum +2A uses the same pinout as the +3.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum +2B and ZX Spectrum +3B were released in 1989.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] They are functionally similar in design to the Spectrum +2A and +3, though changes to the generation of the audio output signal were made to resolve problems with clipping.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The +2B board has no provision for floppy disk controller circuitry, while the +3B motherboard has no provision for connecting an internal tape drive.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Production of all Amstrad Spectrum models ended in 1992.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair Research granted a licence for the ZX Spectrum design to the Timex Corporation in the United States.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Timex marketed several computer models under the Timex Sinclair brand.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] They introduced an enhanced variant of the original Spectrum in the US, known as the Timex Sinclair 2068.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This upgraded model features improvements in sound, graphics, and various other aspects.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] However, Timex's versions were generally not compatible with Sinclair systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Timex of Portugal developed and produced several branded computers, including a PAL region-compatible version of the Timex Sinclair 2068, known as the Timex Computer 2048.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This variant features distinct buffers for both the ULA and the CPU, significantly enhancing compatibility with ZX Spectrum software compared to the American model.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Software developed for the Portuguese-made 2048 remained fully compatible with its American counterpart, as the ROMs were left unaltered.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Timex of Portugal also created a ZX Spectrum "emulator" in cartridge form.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Several other upgrades were introduced, including a BASIC64 cartridge enabling it to utilise high-resolution (512x192) modes.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This model saw significant success in both Portugal and Poland.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In India, Deci Bells Electronics Limited based in Pune, introduced a licensed version of the Spectrum+ in 1988.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Dubbed the "dB Spectrum+", it performed well in the Indian market, selling over 50,000 units and achieving an 80% market share.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Numerous unofficial Spectrum clones were produced, especially in Eastern Europe.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Many small start-ups in the Soviet Union assembled various clones, distributed through poster adverts and street stalls.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Over 50 such clone models existed in total.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] There were also clones produced in South America, such as the Brazilian-made TK90X and TK95, as well as the Argentine Czerweny CZ models.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In the United Kingdom, Spectrum peripheral vendor Miles Gordon Technology (MGT) released the SAM Coupé 8-bit home computer in December 1989.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It was designed to be fully compatible with the ZX Spectrum 48K, housing a Zilog Z80B processor clocked at 6 MHz and 256KB of RAM.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] By this point, the Amiga and Atari ST had taken hold of the market, leaving MGT in eventual receivership in June 1990.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In his book *Retro Tech*, Peter Leigh considers the Sam Coupé to be the "true" successor of the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In 2024, Retro Games released their unnofficial clone of the ZX Spectrum titled "The Spectrum" — named generically so because the ZX trademark is unlicensed from Sinclair — which would include 48 built-in games, a save game option, rewind mode and pre-owned titles load up.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Several peripherals were developed and marketed by Sinclair.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Printer, a small spark printer, was already on the market upon the ZX Spectrum's release, as its computer bus was partially backward-compatible with that of its predecessor, the ZX81.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] It uses two electrically charged styli to burn away the surface of aluminium-coated paper to reveal the black underlay.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Sinclair Research also introduced the ZX Interface 2, which added two joystick ports and a ROM cartridge port.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Although the ZX Microdrives were initially greeted with good reviews, they never became a popular distribution method due to fears over cartridge quality and piracy.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] After the original ZX Spectrum's keyboard received criticism for its "dead flesh" feel, external keyboards became popular.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In 1983, DK'Tronics launched a Light Pen compatible with some drawing software.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The Abbeydale Designers/Watford Electronics SPDOS and KDOS disk drive interfaces were bundled with office productivity software, including the Tasword word processor, Masterfile database, and Omnicalc spreadsheet.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] This bundle, along with OCP's Stock Control, Finance, and Payroll systems, introduced small businesses to streamlined computerised operations.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In 1987 and 1988, Miles Gordon Technology released the DISCiPLE and +D systems.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] These systems had the capability to store memory images as disk snapshots, allowing users to restore the Spectrum to its exact previous state.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Both systems were compatible with the Microdrive command syntax, simplifying the porting of existing software.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] In the mid-1980s, Telemap Group launched a fee-based service allowing ZX Spectrum users to connect their machines to the Micronet 800 information provider via a Prism Micro Products VTX5000 modem.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Micronet 800, hosted by Prestel, provided news and information about microcomputers and offered a form of instant messaging and online shopping.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Most Spectrum software was originally distributed on audio cassette tapes, intended to work with consumer cassette recorders.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Software was also distributed through type-in program listings in magazines and books.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The reader entered a program by hand and saved it to cassette for later use.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Some magazines distributed 7" 331⁄3 rpm flexi disc records, or "Floppy ROMs", a variant of regular vinyl records which could be played on a standard record player.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Some radio stations broadcast audio stream data via frequency modulation or medium wave so listeners could directly record it onto an audio cassette themselves.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] ZX Spectrum-focused radio programmes existed in the United Kingdom, which were received over long distances on domestic radio receivers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Software released for the machine includes programming languages, databases, word processors (*Tasword* being the most prominent), spreadsheets, drawing and painting tools (e.g.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Over 24,000 different software titles were released for the ZX Spectrum throughout its lifespan.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Beginning in August 1982 the ZX Spectrum was bundled with *Horizons: Software Starter Pack*, a compilation of ten demonstration programs.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] The ZX Spectrum has an extensive library of video games which established it as a prominent gaming platform in the 1980s, including *Manic Miner*, *Jet Set Willy*, *Chuckie Egg*, *Elite*, *Sabre Wulf*, *Knight Lore*, and *The Hobbit*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] *Ant Attack* is the first video game with isometric graphics, *Turbo Esprit*, the first open world driving game, and *Redhawk* features the first superhero created specifically for a video game.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Many ZX81 games were rewritten for the Spectrum to take advantage of the newer machine's colour and sound, such as Psion's *Flight Simulation*.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Hardware limitations of the machine required a level of creativity from video game designers.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Initial reception of the ZX Spectrum was generally positive.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Critics in Britain welcomed the new machine as a worthy successor to the ZX81; Robin Bradbeer of *Sinclair User* praised the additional keyboard functions the Spectrum had to offer, and lauded the "strength" of its ergonomic and presentable design.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Tim Hartnell from *Your Computer* noted that Sinclair had improved on the shortcomings of the ZX80 and ZX81 by revamping the Spectrum's load and save functions, noting that it made working with the machine "a pleasure".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p01] Hartnell concluded that despite minor faults, the machine was "way ahead" of its competitors, and its specification exceeded that of the BBC Micro Model A.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The role of the ZX Spectrum in the history of personal computers and video games made it one of the most important and influential computers of the 1980s.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Some observers credit it as being responsible for launching the British information technology industry during a period of recession, while introducing home computing to the masses.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] As of 2024, it is also one of the best-selling British computers of all time, with over five million units sold by the end of the Spectrum's lifespan in 1992.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] It retained the title of Britain's top-selling computer until the Amstrad PCW surpassed it in the 1990s, with eight million units sold by the end of the PCW's lifespan in 1998.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The ZX Spectrum is affectionately known as the "Speccy" by elements of its fan following.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The ZX Spectrum was popular in communist Czechoslovakia, with an estimated 100,000 in the country by 1988 making it the most popular home computer of the time.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] This was despite only briefly being officially distributed, and never advertised.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Its small size made it easier to smuggle into the country to avoid high customs fees.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] A number of notable game developers began their careers on the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Tim and Chris Stamper founded Ultimate Play the Game in 1982, who found success *Jetpac* (1983), *Atic Atac* (1983), *Sabre Wulf* (1984), and *Knight Lore* (1984).
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The Stamper brothers later founded Rare, which became Nintendo's first Western third-party developer.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] David Perry, the founder of Shiny Entertainment, moved from Northern Ireland to England to focus on developing games for the ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Despite the system only having a beeper for audio, musicians such as David Whittaker, Tim Follin and others, created multichannel music for games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Some hobbyists have continued to code for the Spectrum via emulators.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Several games have been released commercially from new software houses such as Cronosoft.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] In 2020, a museum dedicated Sinclair computers opened in Cantanhede, Portugal.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] In 2013, an FPGA-based clone known as the ZX Uno, was announced.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] All of its hardware, firmware and software are open source, released as Creative Commons licence Share-alike.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The use of a Spartan FPGA allows the system to not only re-implement the ZX Spectrum, but many other 8-bit computers and games consoles.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The Uno was successfully crowdfunded in 2016 and the first boards went on sale the same year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] In January 2014, Elite Systems, who produced a successful range of software for the original ZX Spectrum in the 1980s, announced plans for a Spectrum-themed Bluetooth keyboard that would attach to mobile devices.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The company used a crowdfunding campaign to fund the *Recreated ZX Spectrum*, which would be compatible with games the company had already released on iTunes and Google Play.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Elite Systems took down its Spectrum Collection application the following month, due to complaints from authors of the original software that they had not been paid for the content.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] *Wired UK* described the finished device, which was styled as an original Spectrum 48k keyboard, as "absolutely gorgeous" but said it was ultimately more of an expensive novelty than an actual Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] In July 2019, *Eurogamer* reported that many of the orders had yet to be delivered due to a dispute between Elite Systems and their manufacturer, Eurotech.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Later in 2014, the ZX Spectrum Vega retro video game console was announced by Retro Computers and crowdfunded on Indiegogo with the backing of Clive Sinclair.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The Vega, released in 2015, took the form of a handheld TV game but the lack of a full keyboard led to criticism from reviewers due to the large number of text adventures supplied with the device.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Most reviewers branded the device cheap and uncomfortable to use.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The follow-up, the ZX Spectrum Vega+, was designed as a handheld game console.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Despite reaching its crowdfunding target in March 2016, the company failed to fulfil the majority of orders.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Reviewing the Vega+, *The Register* criticised numerous aspects and features of the machine, including its design and build quality and summed up by saying that the "entire feel is plasticky and inconsequential".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Retro Computers Ltd was placed into liquidation in 2019.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The ZX Spectrum Next is an expanded and updated version of the ZX Spectrum computer implemented with FPGA technology funded by a Kickstarter campaign in April 2017, with the board-only computer delivered to backers later that year.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The finished machine, including a case designed by Rick Dickinson who died during the development of the project, was released to backers in February 2020.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] *MagPi* called it "a lovely piece of kit", noting that it is "well-designed and well-built: authentic to the original, and with technology that nods to the past while remaining functional and relevant in the modern age".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] *PC Pro* magazine called the Next "undeniably impressive" while noting that some features were "not quite ready".
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] A further Kickstarter for an improved revision of the hardware was funded in August 2020.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] The ZX Touch is a handheld gaming console, released by Elmar Electronic in November 2023, that uses bare-metal emulation to play ZX Spectrum games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] It features a 7-inch touchscreen, built-in games, and microSD support for loading additional games.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] A running gag in the film *Scott Pilgrim vs. the World* has character Julie Powers censored with ZX Spectrum sound effects.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] Director Edgar Wright stated that he used to wait for Spectrum games to load when he was a teenager.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] On 23 April 2012, a Google doodle honoured the 30th anniversary of the Spectrum.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] As it coincided with St George's Day, the Google logo was of St George fighting a dragon in the style of a Spectrum loading screen.
[src:retro-z80-assembly/zx-spectrum-p02] One of the alternate endings in the interactive film *Black Mirror: Bandersnatch* (2018) includes the main character playing data tape audio that, when loaded into a ZX Spectrum emulator, generates a QR code leading to a website with a playable version of the "Nohzdyve" game from the film.
